WEBVTT

01:25.180 --> 01:27.390
- Hi!
- Ok, Francois?

01:27.391 --> 01:28.317
And you?

01:28.392 --> 01:31.276
Stephane... Francois...

01:31.354 --> 01:35.119
- Still on the team?
- As ready as ever.

01:41.198 --> 01:43.360
Hello.

01:46.787 --> 01:51.332
- This one?
- At the back, please.

02:01.178 --> 02:03.012
Hi, I'm Herve.

02:03.013 --> 02:06.058
A sports teacher here for 3 years.

02:06.392 --> 02:08.685
Welcome to all our new colleagues.

02:08.686 --> 02:11.480
The students can be tough...

02:11.481 --> 02:15.150
but they're good kids.

02:15.151 --> 02:17.736
Hi, I'm Olivier.

02:17.737 --> 02:20.114
I teach physical science...

02:20.115 --> 02:23.836
and I've been here for 4 years.

02:24.286 --> 02:26.120
I'm Patrick,

02:26.121 --> 02:29.791
and I teach multiplication tables,

02:29.792 --> 02:32.127
and sometimes mathematics!

02:32.128 --> 02:34.296
I've been at this school

02:34.297 --> 02:36.507
for a number of years.

02:36.508 --> 02:40.886
Hello, I'm Anne.
I used to work in the Lyon suburbs.

02:40.887 --> 02:42.763
I teach English.

02:42.764 --> 02:45.475
I'm looking for my new colleagues.

02:45.476 --> 02:47.329
Hi, I'm Isabelle

02:47.394 --> 02:48.603
Nice to meet you.

02:48.604 --> 02:50.148
I'm Christiane.

02:50.690 --> 02:55.319
I'm Frederic,
I teach history and geography.

02:55.320 --> 02:57.404
and I used to work
out in suburbs of Paris.

02:57.405 --> 03:01.274
I'm happy to be in the city now.

03:01.368 --> 03:04.871
I'm Julie, the year supervisor.
I'd like to welcome you all

03:04.872 --> 03:08.122
and wish you a good year.

03:08.125 --> 03:10.544
I'm Aline and I'm the cook

03:10.545 --> 03:13.338
I'd like to welcome you all.

03:13.339 --> 03:15.252
Thank you, Aline!

03:16.801 --> 03:21.055
Hello. I'm Gilles,
I've been teaching mathematics

03:21.056 --> 03:25.226
for many years

03:25.227 --> 03:30.106
I'm retiring at the end of this year

03:30.107 --> 03:34.182
I'd like to wish the new arrivals
plenty of courage.

03:37.073 --> 03:40.117
I'm Francois
I teach French.

03:40.118 --> 03:42.703
And I'm starting
my fourth year here

03:42.704 --> 03:45.072
Welcome everybody.

03:53.466 --> 03:55.926
We'll meet up at midday...

03:55.927 --> 03:59.339
in the canteen for a drink
to mark the new year.

04:11.569 --> 04:15.072
You get Wednesday like you wanted!

04:15.073 --> 04:17.911
We could swap our classes

04:19.828 --> 04:22.038
Nice, nice...

04:22.039 --> 04:24.248
Not nice, not nice at all.

04:24.249 --> 04:26.167
He's nice.

04:26.168 --> 04:29.462
Not nice, watch him.
Not nice at all.

04:29.463 --> 04:32.340
Nice, not nice.

04:32.341 --> 04:34.460
She's not nice at all.

04:42.895 --> 04:44.953
Arthur, your cap.

04:46.190 --> 04:48.719
Good morning.

04:50.695 --> 04:53.431
That's my place.

04:54.866 --> 05:00.866
Get lost!

05:24.022 --> 05:26.184
Calm down now!

05:29.570 --> 05:30.952
Stop stirring things up

05:30.988 --> 05:32.781
Remove your hood, please

05:32.782 --> 05:35.742
You two back there,
there's place here.

05:35.743 --> 05:38.203
- One up front.
- There's room here too!

05:38.204 --> 05:41.250
Let's get one thing clear...

05:46.505 --> 05:50.508
We waste 5 minutes
lining outside,

05:50.509 --> 05:52.427
5 coming up, 5 setting down:

05:52.428 --> 05:54.221
15 minutes out of hour

05:54.222 --> 05:57.266
Do you realize
what 15 lost minutes means?

05:57.267 --> 05:58.753
With 25 hours a week

05:58.768 --> 06:00.728
and 30 weeks in the year,

06:00.729 --> 06:03.231
we lose thousands of minutes.

06:03.232 --> 06:06.217
In other schools,
they do a full work.

06:06.694 --> 06:10.415
Imagine how far ahead they get
in a year

06:10.823 --> 06:12.407
Figure it out!

06:12.408 --> 06:14.261
We never do an hour.

06:14.327 --> 06:16.239
Hand up to speak.

06:17.956 --> 06:20.875
We never do an hour
You always say that!

06:20.876 --> 06:25.524
Teachers say we do an hours class
but we never do.

06:27.466 --> 06:30.677
8.30 to 9.25 doesn't make an hour.

06:30.678 --> 06:33.180
All right it's 55 minutes.

06:33.181 --> 06:35.724
That’s an important point

06:35.725 --> 06:40.896
Stop saying other schools do an hour
They don't!

06:40.897 --> 06:44.901
All I'm saying is that
we waste time. Like now.

06:44.902 --> 06:47.320
To start with,

06:47.321 --> 06:49.027
take out a sheet of paper,

06:49.323 --> 06:52.701
fold it in two so that it can stand

06:52.702 --> 06:55.954
on the edge of your desk clearly

06:55.955 --> 06:59.375
and using block capitals,

06:59.376 --> 07:02.128
write your full name.

07:02.129 --> 07:04.046
Why write our names?

07:04.047 --> 07:05.673
To know who you are

07:05.674 --> 07:08.843
- But you know us!
- We had you last year.

07:08.844 --> 07:12.848
Esmeralda,
half of the kids here are new.

07:12.849 --> 07:16.435
Be happy. That way
people will know your name

07:16.436 --> 07:18.020
I'm not doing it

07:18.021 --> 07:21.065
I won't if you don't

07:21.066 --> 07:22.233
You're right

07:22.234 --> 07:27.030
For those of you who don’t know me,
I'm Mr. Marin

07:27.323 --> 07:29.908
- A marine?
- Very funny

07:29.909 --> 07:32.027
Corny!

07:32.537 --> 07:35.213
He wiped you out, sir

07:35.623 --> 07:38.934
Come on, it shouldn’t take so long

07:40.921 --> 07:43.673
Five minutes to write a name

07:43.674 --> 07:45.939
It's ridiculous

08:08.534 --> 08:11.036
A biscuit for the firs day?

08:11.037 --> 08:13.464
I'm OK, thanks

08:15.416 --> 08:19.182
Rachel, a biscuit will buck you up

08:23.801 --> 08:27.387
All right. "Witty"

08:27.388 --> 08:29.962
That's word
we'll try to explain later.

08:30.474 --> 08:32.476
Are there any other words

08:32.477 --> 08:36.036
that you don't understand?

08:36.481 --> 08:39.817
The word "condescension"

08:39.818 --> 08:42.361
Yes, that's a complicated word.

08:42.362 --> 08:44.489
Do you have any idea

08:44.490 --> 08:46.866
what that might mean?

08:46.867 --> 08:49.235
A vague idea but I'm not sure

08:49.745 --> 08:51.496
You're not sure?

08:51.497 --> 08:54.875
We'll talk about that later then

08:54.876 --> 08:58.462
- Yes, Damien
- "Argentine".

08:58.463 --> 09:01.038
Argentine. What does that mean?

09:01.091 --> 09:04.077
It's people who live in Argentina.

09:04.136 --> 09:06.804
Right, the inhabitants of Argentina

09:06.805 --> 09:09.438
Of course not

09:09.517 --> 09:12.091
Damien, who lives in Argentina?

09:12.103 --> 09:13.729
The Argentines

09:13.730 --> 09:16.565
In a soccer match
Argentina's players

09:16.566 --> 09:18.154
are called...

09:18.527 --> 09:20.232
Footballers

09:21.613 --> 09:22.957
Let's move on

09:23.240 --> 09:27.109
Any other difficult words
in the text?

09:27.787 --> 09:29.130
Henriette

09:30.289 --> 09:35.187
Is there anything
that you didn't understand?

09:38.048 --> 09:39.430
"Henceforth".

09:40.675 --> 09:42.019
"Henceforth".

09:42.177 --> 09:43.928
"Henceforth"

09:43.929 --> 09:47.180
Thanks for the prompt, Samantha.

09:50.144 --> 09:54.523
I think that will do,
Let's take a look at these words.

09:54.524 --> 09:57.359
All right. Austrian

09:57.360 --> 10:01.155
Wey was the one
who picked the word Austrian

10:01.156 --> 10:02.532
Yes, Esmeralda.

10:02.533 --> 10:04.993
We all know what "Austrian" is.

10:04.994 --> 10:08.997
- People from Austria.
- Wey doesn't know and...

10:08.998 --> 10:11.291
Maybe, but everyone else knows!

10:11.292 --> 10:15.671
We get the message. You didn't
know "misleading"

10:15.672 --> 10:19.216
...so you're not really
in any position to talk.

10:19.217 --> 10:21.344
But everyone knows
what "Austrian" means.

10:21.345 --> 10:23.668
Nobody's perfect.

10:25.516 --> 10:28.727
- "Austrian" is not a very,
important word, Wey.

10:28.728 --> 10:32.314
It refers to someone
from the land of Austria,

10:32.315 --> 10:34.858
which is pretty tiny country.

10:34.859 --> 10:37.021
We can live without the word.

10:37.278 --> 10:41.240
Can anyone name a famous Austrian?

10:41.241 --> 10:44.654
Mozart.

10:45.162 --> 10:47.914
- Who?
- Wol Fang Amadeus Mozart.

10:47.915 --> 10:52.002
- "Wol Fung" maybe if he
were English, not Austrian.

10:52.003 --> 10:54.922
Any other famous Austrians?

10:54.923 --> 10:58.335
Austria could vanish
no one would notice.

10:59.261 --> 11:02.638
Seriously, it's south of Germany.
So check a map, Wey,

11:02.639 --> 11:05.725
You'll see where it is.

11:05.726 --> 11:06.550
Souleymane,

11:06.644 --> 11:08.895
...can you note the words too?

11:08.896 --> 11:10.484
I forgot my things.

11:10.898 --> 11:13.483
No one can land you some paper...

11:13.484 --> 11:16.445
I'll do it at home.

11:16.446 --> 11:19.281
You'll do it at home. Sure you will.
That's your approach

11:19.282 --> 11:20.992
Only work at home.

11:20.993 --> 11:22.451
I'm serious!

11:22.452 --> 11:27.290
If I could be sure of that...

11:27.291 --> 11:29.960
Don't worry. It'll be ok

11:29.961 --> 11:33.213
Let's move on to "succulent".

11:33.214 --> 11:36.832
"Succulent" is a word that we'll try
to guess the meaning of.

11:37.469 --> 11:39.053
What's is "succulent"?

11:39.054 --> 11:40.397
Suck

11:40.722 --> 11:42.884
Suck off.

11:43.642 --> 11:45.392
Very funny, Boubacar.

11:45.436 --> 11:46.980
Very witty indeed,

11:48.606 --> 11:50.355
Here's a sentence...

11:51.108 --> 11:53.360
...with "succulent".

11:53.361 --> 11:59.361
"Bill enjoys a succulent..."

12:00.368 --> 12:01.702
"...cheeseburger."

12:01.703 --> 12:03.660
Cheeseburgers stink!

12:04.707 --> 12:06.791
- Who said that?
- Me.

12:06.792 --> 12:08.542
Why "cheeseburger"?

12:09.128 --> 12:15.128
Well, since you say that, you
think cheeseburgers aren't succulent.

12:15.260 --> 12:17.428
Maybe, but they're crap.

12:17.429 --> 12:21.557
OK, but what I just said
should have made the penny drop.

12:21.558 --> 12:23.851
- What does that mean?
- Mean what?

12:23.852 --> 12:25.705
The penny thing...

12:27.273 --> 12:28.565
To make the penny drop,

12:28.566 --> 12:31.777
No one knows the expression?

12:31.778 --> 12:34.196
If the penny drops,
it means you understand.

12:34.197 --> 12:36.115
When I say,

12:36.116 --> 12:40.703
if cheeseburger stink
they're not succulent,

12:40.704 --> 12:44.248
that should help you see
what "succulent" means.

12:44.249 --> 12:47.544
- What's with the Bills?
- What bills?

12:47.545 --> 12:49.030
The name Bill.

12:49.630 --> 12:51.882
You always use weird names.

12:51.883 --> 12:55.344
Weird? A recent US President
was called Bill.

12:55.345 --> 12:59.974
Why don't you use Aissata
or Rachid or Ahmed...

12:59.975 --> 13:02.018
You always use whitey names.

13:02.019 --> 13:03.362
What names?

13:03.437 --> 13:06.791
- Honky names.
- What's honky?

13:07.399 --> 13:10.527
Honkies, Frenchies, frogs.

13:10.528 --> 13:11.820
You're not French?

13:11.821 --> 13:13.526
No, I'm not French.

13:13.656 --> 13:15.142
I didn't know.

13:15.158 --> 13:16.700
I am, but not proud of it.

13:16.701 --> 13:20.162
Fine, I'm not either

13:20.163 --> 13:22.164
Why use these names?

13:22.165 --> 13:26.628
Khoumba, if I start choosing names

13:26.629 --> 13:29.589
to suit all your origins, it'll
never end.

13:29.590 --> 13:31.649
Just change a little!

13:33.344 --> 13:35.712
What do you suggest?

13:35.889 --> 13:38.015
Aissata! Fatou, no!

13:38.016 --> 13:40.796
- No, Aissata.
- Aissata, Aissata!

14:11.010 --> 14:14.555
Excuse me. You have class 4/3
in French?

14:14.556 --> 14:16.473
I'm class supervisor too.

14:16.474 --> 14:19.563
Know what book you'll be reading?

14:19.770 --> 14:22.446
No, I haven't decided.

14:23.065 --> 14:28.069
In history I'll start with
Ancien Regime

14:28.070 --> 14:33.955
If you want to link into that,
what kind of books are there?

14:35.036 --> 14:38.539
The Enlightenment will
be tough for them.

14:38.540 --> 14:41.667
How about Voltaire? Is he tough?

14:41.668 --> 14:43.920
He's not easy.

14:43.921 --> 14:45.626
Candide, is simple...

14:46.674 --> 14:48.586
Not in their year

14:48.884 --> 14:50.370
Zadig...

14:50.970 --> 14:55.148
Yes, but it'd be tough

15:29.387 --> 15:30.762
You have 20 seconds.

15:30.763 --> 15:32.676
No, we've not finished yet!

15:33.057 --> 15:35.559
We've not finished yet!

15:35.560 --> 15:38.134
We can't spend 2 hours on the
imperfect.

15:41.608 --> 15:44.137
Dalla, I can give you the time.

15:47.448 --> 15:49.462
Sir, my pen keeps leaking!

15:49.992 --> 15:52.160
- It's crap
- Who has a handkerchief?

15:52.161 --> 15:53.647
Me!

15:54.080 --> 15:55.006
Rabah!

15:55.081 --> 15:58.228
Ask before you stand.

15:59.336 --> 16:01.865
- May I?
- Yes.

16:03.841 --> 16:06.718
- Gently, Ok...
- The perv!

16:06.719 --> 16:08.094
He touched her tits!

16:08.095 --> 16:10.472
Just give him the handkerchief.

16:10.473 --> 16:13.600
Spare us your comments.

16:13.601 --> 16:15.969
God dam pedophile!

16:16.980 --> 16:19.922
- Quiet!
- Sir?

16:20.317 --> 16:24.656
Why the imperfect indicative?

16:25.030 --> 16:27.991
Cut it out!

16:27.992 --> 16:31.953
- Why not just imperfect?
- Quiet, Souleymane.

16:31.954 --> 16:35.165
All right, Esmeralda,
why the indicative?

16:35.166 --> 16:38.586
If I knew, I wouldn't ask.

16:38.587 --> 16:43.633
I can imagine. Anyone know why we
specify the imperfect indicative?

16:43.634 --> 16:45.927
Why not just the imperfect?

16:45.928 --> 16:48.930
Nassim?
May I wash my hands?

16:48.931 --> 16:51.873
Go on, wash them and get it over with.

16:52.059 --> 16:54.019
Make it quick.

16:54.020 --> 16:56.035
He'll take a week!

16:56.856 --> 16:58.871
- I'll go with him.
- Enough

16:59.276 --> 17:00.761
The imperfect indicative is

17:02.571 --> 17:05.881
different than another imperfect

17:06.408 --> 17:08.365
Which imperfect is that?

17:08.703 --> 17:11.580
Agam?
- The imperfect subjunctive.

17:11.581 --> 17:12.914
Exactly.

17:12.915 --> 17:18.344
The Imperfect subjunctive.
Can anyone give me an example?

17:19.714 --> 17:22.383
I don't believe it, Khoumba,
but go on.

17:22.384 --> 17:26.679
I may be wrong...

17:26.680 --> 17:28.306
I think so too.

17:28.307 --> 17:30.308
- I were
- I were.

17:30.309 --> 17:32.561
From the verb "to werr"

17:32.562 --> 17:34.646
- I don't know...
- I wuz.

17:34.647 --> 17:37.358
I were, we were, you were

17:37.359 --> 17:41.445
All right. Not bad but you use it
wrongly.

17:41.446 --> 17:46.576
You vaguely recall
the imperfect subjunctive.

17:46.577 --> 17:48.745
Imagine I say:

17:48.746 --> 17:51.623
"He insist..."

17:51.624 --> 17:54.301
"that I be..."

17:55.879 --> 17:59.465
Let's say "in shape".
"He insists that I be in shape"

17:59.466 --> 18:02.593
What is "be" in that example?

18:02.594 --> 18:04.846
The present subjunctive.

18:04.847 --> 18:08.349
Very good. For the imperfect
subjunctive,

18:08.350 --> 18:12.521
we follow the sequence of tenses
and use a past:

18:12.522 --> 18:13.897
"He insisted..."

18:13.898 --> 18:16.775
- "He insisted that I..."
Khoumba?

18:16.776 --> 18:19.111
- Were.
- Were. Yes.

18:19.112 --> 18:21.697
You really think I'll tell my mom:

18:21.698 --> 18:25.410
"He insisted that I were'd been in shape?"

18:25.411 --> 18:29.122
Not I were'd been.
Learn to use it first

18:29.123 --> 18:31.875
"That I were in shape"

18:31.876 --> 18:34.920
- The sequence of tenses.
- No one says that.

18:34.921 --> 18:37.464
I was right!

18:37.465 --> 18:40.009
"I were".

18:40.010 --> 18:43.513
Will you let me answer the question?

18:43.514 --> 18:45.932
If you care.
- You may.

18:45.933 --> 18:50.604
- Before mastering something,
the imperfect subjunctive,

18:50.605 --> 18:53.607
you're telling me it's no use.

18:53.608 --> 18:56.568
Start by mastering it,

18:56.569 --> 19:00.239
then you can call its use into question.

19:00.240 --> 19:02.783
Sir, why are you criticizing us?

19:02.784 --> 19:07.205
They're right, that's the way
people talked in the old days.

19:07.206 --> 19:10.083
Even my gran didn't say that.

19:10.084 --> 19:13.170
Or your great granddad
It's from the Middle Ages!

19:13.171 --> 19:14.963
No it isn't.

19:14.964 --> 19:16.840
It is!

19:16.841 --> 19:18.300
It's bourgeois...

19:18.301 --> 19:23.181
Tell me, when was the last time

19:23.182 --> 19:24.807
you heard someone talk like that?

19:24.808 --> 19:28.436
Yesterday, with friends,
we used the imperfect subjunctive.

19:28.437 --> 19:30.021
No, someone normal!

19:30.022 --> 19:33.191
All right, all right.

19:33.192 --> 19:35.861
The people on the streets...

19:35.862 --> 19:38.539
Can I reply?

19:40.200 --> 19:41.543
Yep.

19:41.702 --> 19:44.495
I'll talk this over, but calmly.

19:44.496 --> 19:48.291
All right, not everyone talks that way.

19:48.292 --> 19:51.378
In fact, people who do are pretty rare.

19:51.379 --> 19:54.298
I'd even say only snobs...

19:54.299 --> 19:57.676
...use the imperfect subjunctive.

19:57.677 --> 19:59.970
What's a snob?

19:59.971 --> 20:04.267
Snobs are slightly affected,
slightly precious people

20:04.268 --> 20:06.853
who tend to put on airs.

20:06.854 --> 20:08.197
Homosexuals?

20:09.523 --> 20:12.304
No, not homosexuals...

20:12.610 --> 20:14.528
You can be affected and refined

20:14.529 --> 20:18.073
without being homosexual.

20:18.074 --> 20:20.201
In any case,

20:20.202 --> 20:24.580
this register may seem
formal and a bit affected,

20:24.581 --> 20:26.875
and even bourgeois.

20:26.876 --> 20:30.879
But these different registers exist

20:30.880 --> 20:33.173
...as I keep telling you,

20:33.174 --> 20:37.428
...you need to be able to use them

20:37.429 --> 20:39.972
...Familiar, current, formal,
oral and written.

20:39.973 --> 20:42.505
Move between them
and use them all. Yes, Lucie?

20:42.517 --> 20:47.313
How do we know what's written
and what's for oral?

20:47.314 --> 20:50.317
Why is a word more one for one register?

20:50.318 --> 20:53.111
Normally, that's something

20:53.112 --> 20:57.039
that you pick up as you go along

20:57.117 --> 21:00.619
You need to use intuition.

21:00.620 --> 21:02.788
What's this?

21:02.789 --> 21:06.584
Intuition is when you can't use thinking

21:06.585 --> 21:10.547
When you can't really...

21:10.548 --> 21:13.258
It's not knowing
but more like sensing something.

21:13.259 --> 21:15.583
When you sense things

21:16.054 --> 21:18.275
What if you don't sense?

21:19.141 --> 21:21.892
If you don't sense them, well...

21:21.893 --> 21:25.271
You gain intuition
by using the language.

21:25.272 --> 21:28.817
That's when you learn to distinguish...

21:28.818 --> 21:32.230
almost automatically
between oral and written styles.

21:32.530 --> 21:35.824
- Souleymane wants to say something.
- Shut it.

21:35.825 --> 21:37.701
What does he want to say?

21:37.702 --> 21:39.188
Go on!

21:39.329 --> 21:42.683
Calm down

21:43.625 --> 21:45.668
Cut it out. No fighting

21:45.669 --> 21:48.338
- I'll whop you
- Don't act tough!

21:48.339 --> 21:52.678
What's wrong? Boubacar, turn around.

21:54.053 --> 21:56.377
- What is it?
- Nothing

21:56.389 --> 22:00.729
- Apparently not.
- Don't send him to the principal.

22:01.144 --> 22:03.938
If I tell you,
I'm good for Guantanamo.

22:03.939 --> 22:05.732
Guantanamo! Guantanamo!

22:05.733 --> 22:07.115
I'll be tased!

22:07.151 --> 22:08.494
You won't be tased.

22:09.946 --> 22:11.655
- You have a question?
- Yep

22:11.656 --> 22:12.823
So ask it

22:12.824 --> 22:16.160
- It's too wicked
- It's not

22:16.161 --> 22:18.370
It's the pits for you
- Just ask it

22:18.371 --> 22:20.414
- I have your word?
- Hurry up

22:20.415 --> 22:24.252
This is what I heard, ok?
I didn't say it but I heard...

22:24.253 --> 22:27.607
People say you like men.

22:32.345 --> 22:34.096
I didn't say it!

22:34.097 --> 22:37.057
- Who says that?
- Just people

22:37.058 --> 22:39.393
"They say Mr. Marin likes men"

22:39.394 --> 22:41.556
Others say that, not you?

22:41.563 --> 22:44.232
- You not interested?
- No way

22:44.233 --> 22:46.818
- So why do you ask?
- For the others.

22:46.819 --> 22:48.445
I'm spokesman

22:48.446 --> 22:52.109
- But you don't care?
- If you like men, fine

22:53.034 --> 22:56.120
- So is it true?
- You are asking me.

22:56.121 --> 22:59.475
Homosexual isn’t an insult, sir.

23:00.250 --> 23:02.877
You say it isn't but it seems
to be a problem for you.

23:02.878 --> 23:06.756
You find it odd, men liking men.

23:06.757 --> 23:10.760
Maybe it is, I don't know
It is true or not?

23:10.761 --> 23:13.263
No, it's not. Feel better now?

23:13.264 --> 23:14.608
Yeah? Sure.

23:17.310 --> 23:19.678
Sorry to disappoint you.

23:21.440 --> 23:24.650
All right, if Souleymane doesn't mind

23:24.651 --> 23:27.153
now he's settle his hang-ups,

23:27.154 --> 23:30.038
let's get back
to the imperfect indicative.

23:34.871 --> 23:37.092
Yeah, like that! Not bad

23:43.172 --> 23:44.964
- What are you doing?
- Stop.

23:44.965 --> 23:46.671
- What's up?
- Get lost

23:50.930 --> 23:53.890
Who asked you? Look at your mug
- Get lost

23:53.891 --> 23:56.185
- It's fucking ok!
Take these jerks,

23:56.186 --> 23:57.686
then we'll see

23:57.687 --> 24:00.022
Go on, show me your backs

24:00.023 --> 24:03.170
- These guys suck.
- Another one.

24:03.193 --> 24:05.987
- Classy display
- You bet

24:05.988 --> 24:08.615
- Got one for me?
- Can't afford it

24:08.616 --> 24:10.325
- How much?
- Too much!

24:10.326 --> 24:13.371
Stop thinking I'm broke like you!

24:18.376 --> 24:22.421
She screwed up there
She thinks it's regular verb

24:22.422 --> 24:25.099
No the verb's swim. Swimmed.

24:32.725 --> 24:36.447
Justine! "Swimmed"!

24:37.772 --> 24:40.199
Justine, work it out yourself

24:41.693 --> 24:45.724
Swummed. That's better,
it mixes the two.

24:45.823 --> 24:48.499
Swammed!

24:50.828 --> 24:54.388
She put swemmed

24:56.543 --> 25:00.264
- Ok, thank you
- Try swommed

25:00.797 --> 25:03.268
You can sit down

25:03.550 --> 25:04.759
Let's see.

25:04.760 --> 25:06.594
Let's see

25:06.595 --> 25:08.552
She can’t write

25:09.056 --> 25:11.516
She can’t write? Can you, Rabah?

25:11.517 --> 25:13.393
- You bet
- Go on then

25:13.394 --> 25:15.409
Conjugate it properly

25:17.857 --> 25:19.201
- Swummed
- No

25:20.152 --> 25:21.799
Continue.

25:24.698 --> 25:26.950
Swammed

25:26.951 --> 25:28.294
Wrong again

25:30.705 --> 25:33.790
Just kidding

25:33.791 --> 25:36.262
- It’s not like that
- So what is it?

25:38.880 --> 25:40.528
Without an I

25:40.716 --> 25:42.774
Right, no I

25:43.552 --> 25:46.137
Why make fun of Justine,

25:46.138 --> 25:49.391
when you can’t do better?

25:49.392 --> 25:52.644
Justine wasn’t so wrong

25:52.645 --> 25:55.896
That’s enough

25:58.818 --> 26:02.530
You cant focus for more
than 20 seconds

26:02.531 --> 26:04.178
like 3 year olds

26:04.366 --> 26:08.286
People aged 14 or 15
like you’re supposed to be

26:08.287 --> 26:11.748
If I ask a question
they should know

26:11.749 --> 26:14.501
Your kidding around goes too far!

26:14.502 --> 26:15.878
Not at all

26:15.879 --> 26:18.255
- Everyone thinks so
- Dead right

26:18.256 --> 26:21.509
Everyone thinks so
or only you think so?

26:21.510 --> 26:23.010
No, everyone!

26:23.011 --> 26:26.306
I think you push it.

26:26.307 --> 26:31.812
If I cut you some slack,
you'll never get anywhere

26:31.813 --> 26:33.939
You go too far!

26:33.940 --> 26:36.617
And you know why

26:39.946 --> 26:43.950
I’m sick of these clowns!
Sick of them!

26:43.951 --> 26:46.578
I can’t take any more

26:46.579 --> 26:50.332
They’re nothing,
they know nothing...

26:50.333 --> 26:54.044
they look right through you
when you try to teach them

26:54.045 --> 26:56.004
They cat stay in their shit

26:56.005 --> 26:57.962
I’m not going to help them

26:59.259 --> 27:02.261
They’re so basic, so insincere

27:02.262 --> 27:04.389
...always looking for trouble

27:04.390 --> 27:06.099
Go ahead, guys

27:06.100 --> 27:08.435
...Stay in your crap neighborhood

27:08.436 --> 27:12.606
You’ll be here all yours lives
and it serves you right

27:12.607 --> 27:18.195
Ill see the principal and tell him
I’m not working with 3/2 again.

27:18.196 --> 27:22.533
No more technology
for the rest of the year. Too bad

27:22.534 --> 27:26.829
It’s been three months now and
they haven’t done a single thing

27:26.830 --> 27:31.001
Have you seen them in the yard?
It’s like they’re in heat

27:31.002 --> 27:34.880
They’re all over each other,
like animals

27:34.881 --> 27:36.058
It’s crazy. It’s the same in class

27:36.132 --> 27:40.207
Kevin spent a whole hour doing

27:40.929 --> 27:45.827
I’ve never seen the like
of it in 5 years!

27:49.146 --> 27:52.397
Enough, no more!

27:52.442 --> 27:55.427
We’re not animals!

28:01.535 --> 28:03.653
Sorry I’m...

28:05.456 --> 28:07.205
It’s dumb.

28:11.754 --> 28:15.724
Come on. Let's get some air

28:24.476 --> 28:27.187
One extract isn’t a lot to read

28:27.188 --> 28:29.555
No one did it?

28:31.984 --> 28:34.412
We’re wasting time here

28:34.821 --> 28:36.983
Let’s read it again then

28:38.074 --> 28:39.662
Who wants to read?

28:42.788 --> 28:46.624
Great! Excellent work
atmosphere today.

28:46.625 --> 28:48.434
Khoumba, go on.

28:49.086 --> 28:50.430
No way.

28:51.130 --> 28:52.474
You won’t read?

28:52.673 --> 28:54.630
I don’t want to

28:54.634 --> 28:57.761
The class revolves
around your desires?

28:57.762 --> 29:00.954
- I don’t want to read
- Don’t care

29:02.768 --> 29:04.886
What did Khoumba just do?

29:05.354 --> 29:07.272
- Wey?
- Sneer

29:07.273 --> 29:10.442
I meant her attitude,
What did she show?

29:10.443 --> 29:12.914
Insolence.

29:13.237 --> 29:15.561
That’s right, you’re an expert

29:18.702 --> 29:22.330
You’re all angrulo with me

29:22.331 --> 29:24.415
What is this?
- That’s not true

29:24.416 --> 29:28.034
Try saying it in French. What am I?

29:28.337 --> 29:29.671
Angrulo

29:29.672 --> 29:31.381
Say it in everyday French

29:31.382 --> 29:33.968
- You’ve got it in for me
- That’s normal French

29:38.306 --> 29:39.932
I just want you to read

29:39.933 --> 29:43.269
I have the right to ask you
to read, don’t I?

29:43.270 --> 29:45.123
Don’t you think so?
- No.

29:45.856 --> 29:46.940
No one has read it

29:46.941 --> 29:49.818
and you’re picking on me.

29:49.819 --> 29:51.695
I’m not. I want to work

29:51.696 --> 29:54.740
and I’ve chosen you
as I have the rights to.

29:54.741 --> 29:56.084
Drop it.

29:56.117 --> 29:58.577
Shut up and start reading

29:58.578 --> 30:00.162
I won’t read

30:00.163 --> 30:04.208
You tell me to shut up,
then to read. What is this?

30:04.209 --> 30:05.651
What’s what?

30:05.669 --> 30:07.128
Make your mind up,

30:07.129 --> 30:08.713
Think it through

30:08.714 --> 30:11.424
Well talk it over after class

30:11.425 --> 30:13.484
It won’t be fun
- Sure

30:13.678 --> 30:16.311
You won’t say that later

30:16.848 --> 30:21.227
Esmeralda, are you on strike too
or can you read for us?

30:21.228 --> 30:23.020
It’s her life

30:23.021 --> 30:26.024
In that case, will you read for us?

30:26.025 --> 30:28.276
I'd be delighted to

30:28.277 --> 30:30.195
All right, were listening

30:30.196 --> 30:31.446
"Dear Kitty"

30:31.447 --> 30:35.117
I’m known as a bundle
of contradictions.

30:35.118 --> 30:37.703
"As I’ve told you several times...

30:37.704 --> 30:40.664
..."my soul is split in two

30:40.665 --> 30:43.417
"my mocking approach to
everything, my joy in life,

30:43.418 --> 30:45.378
..."On one side

30:45.379 --> 30:47.130
my exuberant cheerfulness

30:47.131 --> 30:50.759
..."and my ability
to take things lightly

30:50.760 --> 30:54.763
"By that I mean not seeing
any wrong in flirting...

30:54.764 --> 30:58.642
..."giving a kiss, embracing someone,

30:58.643 --> 31:01.423
..."or telling a tasteless joke

31:01.480 --> 31:04.816
"That side lies in wait
pushing back the other side...

31:04.817 --> 31:09.571
"..." which is more beautiful,
purer and deeper.

31:09.572 --> 31:11.531
"The truth is that no one knows,

31:11.532 --> 31:14.368
..."Anne's better side...

31:14.369 --> 31:16.495
..."and that's why most people...

31:16.496 --> 31:17.913
..."can't stand me.

31:17.914 --> 31:22.251
"I can be an amusing clown
for an afternoon

31:22.252 --> 31:26.005
..."but then everyone

31:26.006 --> 31:29.884
"has had enough of me,

31:29.885 --> 31:31.866
..."So the nice Anne has never once,

31:31.888 --> 31:33.013
..."been seen in company

31:33.014 --> 31:36.684
"But, in her loneliness,
she always triumphs."

31:36.685 --> 31:39.436
"My best to you. Anne Franck.
Anne's diary ends here"

31:39.437 --> 31:41.230
It ends here. Why?

31:41.231 --> 31:45.109
Because the police turned up
at the rooms

31:45.110 --> 31:47.862
...where they were hiding
and deported them.

31:47.863 --> 31:49.305
She died shortly after

31:49.323 --> 31:53.452
...That's what I asked earlier
We talked about it.

31:53.453 --> 31:56.246
I learn about Anne Frank

31:56.247 --> 32:00.459
because she talks about herself
and so I get to know her.

32:00.460 --> 32:04.881
When I ask you to write
your own self-portraits,

32:04.882 --> 32:06.799
...I'll expect the same.

32:06.800 --> 32:10.720
...In other words, to learn things
through your feelings,

32:10.721 --> 32:13.663
...You can talk about facts...

32:13.850 --> 32:18.910
...that will allow
me to know you better.

32:19.773 --> 32:22.108
Yes, Lucie?

32:22.109 --> 32:24.235
What we write

32:24.236 --> 32:30.158
won't be as gripping as...
as what Anne Franck wrote

32:30.159 --> 32:33.870
Our lives aren't as gripping.
- All right

32:33.871 --> 32:35.215
Juliette?

32:36.499 --> 32:40.169
Someone aged 70
could talk about their life,

32:40.170 --> 32:45.425
...but we have nothing to tell at 13,

32:45.426 --> 32:49.137
At 14, 15 or even 13
you've had experiences

32:49.138 --> 32:52.963
- Less then someone aged 70
They’ve live a lot more.

32:54.477 --> 32:56.270
- OK
- They’ve seen life.

32:56.271 --> 33:00.357
It’s funny. You don’t think
your lives are interesting.

33:00.358 --> 33:04.183
We just come to school, go home,
eat and sleep.

33:04.822 --> 33:07.866
You come to school, eat, sleep, fine

33:07.867 --> 33:10.911
The bare facts of your life are dull

33:10.912 --> 33:15.040
But what you feel is interesting
- That’s my business

33:15.041 --> 33:17.668
Maybe, but I’m interested

33:17.669 --> 33:19.545
That’s different

33:19.546 --> 33:21.134
Why is it different?

33:22.090 --> 33:24.665
Because you're a teacher.

33:24.885 --> 33:27.011
It’s not the teacher talking.

33:27.012 --> 33:29.234
- It’s the human being
- It’s your job

33:31.809 --> 33:35.270
I think you’re only saying that
to get us to talk and stuff

33:35.271 --> 33:37.433
...but its not true.

33:38.608 --> 33:40.040
It isn’t? What isn’t true?

33:40.110 --> 33:44.947
The fact that you’re interested
in knowing all that

33:44.948 --> 33:47.033
So I’m not interested at all

33:47.034 --> 33:49.619
...and I’m pushing at this

33:49.620 --> 33:51.913
...to convince you its interesting?

33:51.914 --> 33:55.062
Not as much as you say

33:55.084 --> 33:58.276
Maybe I am exaggerating a little.

33:58.547 --> 34:02.508
It’s only natural since
you don’t agree with me

34:02.509 --> 34:05.053
But, deep down, I’m totally sincere

34:05.054 --> 34:09.099
Why it is such a problem for you

34:09.100 --> 34:11.768
...to talk about your lives?
Boubacar.

34:11.769 --> 34:14.093
Well there stuff...

34:15.064 --> 34:17.021
There’s private stuff.

34:17.025 --> 34:19.610
Of course

34:19.611 --> 34:24.465
What could be hard to say
about your private lives?

34:24.491 --> 34:25.461
Burak.

34:25.534 --> 34:29.300
- We may be ashamed
to say certain things

34:29.705 --> 34:32.207
Yes, it has to do with shame.

34:32.208 --> 34:36.444
Things you find it hard to say
and even harder to write.

34:37.839 --> 34:40.424
On your life, when were you ashamed?

34:40.425 --> 34:44.095
You can be ashamed of pal's mom...

34:44.096 --> 34:47.243
Why? Because you find her ugly?

34:49.143 --> 34:52.104
No. For instance, Rabah's mom,

34:52.105 --> 34:54.481
She offered me lunch but I refused

34:54.482 --> 34:56.188
because I was ashamed

34:56.568 --> 34:58.273
Ashamed to eat with her?

34:58.570 --> 35:01.408
Because it’s beneath you?
- No.

35:01.615 --> 35:04.325
I don’t understand, Tell me why.

35:04.326 --> 35:08.580
I’m ashamed to eat with her
because I respect her.

35:08.581 --> 35:11.958
You never eat with people who
you respect?

35:11.959 --> 35:15.416
I mean, she’s not my girlfriend!

35:15.880 --> 35:20.176
You can only eat with
a girlfriend...

35:20.177 --> 35:22.678
Tell me why. I’m interested

35:22.679 --> 35:25.598
I can’t explain it.
In any case, I’m ashamed

35:25.599 --> 35:29.811
I always hang out with Rabah

35:29.812 --> 35:32.397
so I respect his mom

35:32.398 --> 35:34.207
I don’t eat in front of her

35:34.484 --> 35:38.946
So if Boubacar eats in front of us
he doesn’t respects us

35:38.947 --> 35:40.756
No, it’s not that!

35:42.409 --> 35:46.329
- You can’t understand.
- I’m not smart enough?

35:46.330 --> 35:49.165
You just can’t understand.

35:49.166 --> 35:50.034
Rabah?

35:50.126 --> 35:53.003
I was at a party with Camemberters

35:53.004 --> 35:54.880
Camemberters?

35:54.881 --> 35:56.173
Yeah, like you

35:56.174 --> 35:57.517
What's a Camemberter?

35:57.759 --> 36:00.136
Someone who stinks of cheese

36:00.137 --> 36:04.432
So the people at the party
stank of cheese?

36:04.433 --> 36:06.935
They were all in suits and ties.

36:06.936 --> 36:10.188
I was in my baggies and
got these weird looks

36:10.189 --> 36:12.065
You were ashamed?

36:12.066 --> 36:13.650
Because of the looks

36:13.651 --> 36:16.487
They were embarrassed because of you

36:16.488 --> 36:18.405
...and you felt the same

36:18.406 --> 36:20.074
They weren’t embarrassed

36:20.075 --> 36:23.453
They looked at me
like I was an E.T.

36:23.454 --> 36:24.662
You are an E.T.!

36:24.663 --> 36:26.789
"Why’s that Arab here?"

36:26.790 --> 36:28.833
Ok, so it was a race thing

36:28.834 --> 36:31.753
I don’t know

36:31.754 --> 36:34.490
But the snacks were bacon-flavored

36:36.968 --> 36:39.804
So I... abstained

36:39.805 --> 36:44.142
Right. Bacon, ham... Ok, I get it

36:44.143 --> 36:45.435
Wey...

36:45.436 --> 36:48.480
Young people now have no shame.

36:48.481 --> 36:50.908
Young people now? Like you?

36:50.983 --> 36:52.109
Yeah

36:52.110 --> 36:55.464
- Drop your briefs!
- They have no shame

36:55.572 --> 36:58.455
It’s normal. Always normal

36:58.491 --> 37:00.242
Are you like them?

37:00.243 --> 37:02.161
- No.
- Are you ashamed?

37:02.162 --> 37:04.633
Yes, ashamed of them.

37:07.168 --> 37:09.433
I’ll waste your ugly mug!

37:11.005 --> 37:14.967
Anyone can speak, but
you stay polite, OK.

37:14.968 --> 37:18.053
So why are you ashamed for them?

37:18.054 --> 37:21.349
They have no shame

37:21.350 --> 37:23.893
They yell, they hit each other.
They make jokes,

37:23.894 --> 37:26.321
bother others. No shame

37:26.397 --> 37:28.440
Wey, aren’t you confusing

37:28.441 --> 37:30.150
shame and discipline?

37:30.151 --> 37:32.694
You find the others...

37:32.695 --> 37:34.571
rowdy and impolite.

37:34.572 --> 37:38.033
It can be shameful too

37:38.034 --> 37:38.755
Louise?

37:38.869 --> 37:41.370
You can be ashamed of your appearance

37:41.371 --> 37:44.123
Absolutely

37:44.124 --> 37:47.001
Tell me Louise

37:47.002 --> 37:49.988
what are you ashamed of?

37:52.592 --> 37:54.259
My ears

37:54.260 --> 37:55.719
Your ears?

37:55.720 --> 37:58.088
Can we see? You’re ashamed of your ears?

37:59.307 --> 38:01.517
What’s wrong with them?

38:01.518 --> 38:03.770
They stick out

38:03.771 --> 38:06.439
- You think they stick out
- Mine too

38:06.440 --> 38:08.483
I think that covers it all.

38:08.484 --> 38:12.112
You have all you need
to figure it out

38:12.113 --> 38:15.467
Take out your exercise books.

38:16.242 --> 38:21.920
Note the following exercise
for next Thursday

38:24.376 --> 38:29.392
It’s very simple:
Write your self portrait.

38:34.429 --> 38:36.847
A self-portrait
isn’t an autobiography.

38:36.848 --> 38:40.601
I don’t want your life story

38:40.602 --> 38:43.235
Describe yourself and your personality.

38:44.815 --> 38:46.399
We’ll read them in class

38:46.400 --> 38:49.489
...and see how we can use them

39:00.040 --> 39:02.305
Khoumba.

39:02.459 --> 39:05.504
You know I want to see you

39:10.676 --> 39:12.761
Give me your report book

39:12.762 --> 39:13.732
Why?

39:13.805 --> 39:16.070
You know why.

39:21.605 --> 39:24.691
No, give it to me. Politely.

39:24.692 --> 39:26.913
That’s enough now

39:26.986 --> 39:30.296
Put your photo on it

39:35.119 --> 39:37.788
Is it normal to refuse to read

39:37.789 --> 39:40.124
when teacher asks you to?
Is that normal?

39:40.125 --> 39:42.585
There’s others in the class.

39:42.586 --> 39:45.129
I can’t turn a blind eye to this.

39:45.130 --> 39:46.631
Can I?

39:46.632 --> 39:48.220
OK.

39:51.053 --> 39:53.995
What happened this summer?

39:54.849 --> 39:57.267
What happened during the vacation?

39:57.268 --> 39:59.228
- I didn’t see you
- I know.

39:59.229 --> 40:00.813
I’m intrigued.

40:00.814 --> 40:02.481
At the end of the year in June

40:02.482 --> 40:05.234
...we’d gotten on pretty well together

40:05.235 --> 40:08.071
You participated in class.

40:08.072 --> 40:10.740
Since September,
since the start of this year,

40:10.741 --> 40:13.316
You’re not cooperative,

40:13.453 --> 40:17.331
...You keep sulking,
You refuse to read... What happened?

40:17.332 --> 40:20.751
I don’t like reading now.
Can you hurry, please?

40:20.752 --> 40:23.076
No, I won’t hurry!

40:29.512 --> 40:30.846
Explain.

40:30.847 --> 40:34.308
Why have things changed
all of a sudden?

40:34.309 --> 40:36.780
I can’t stay a kid forever

40:37.312 --> 40:39.939
So it’s a kid thing to cooperate?

40:39.940 --> 40:42.900
That's it
- There's others in the class.

40:42.901 --> 40:44.960
Of course, when you work, it's

40:47.239 --> 40:48.948
I haven’t finished.

40:48.949 --> 40:50.784
My moms waiting for me

40:50.785 --> 40:53.286
I want an apology first

40:53.287 --> 40:56.171
An apology for what you did

40:56.583 --> 40:59.043
"I apologize for
being insolent, sir"

40:59.044 --> 40:59.808
Sorry. Ok?

40:59.961 --> 41:02.505
No, not sorry.

41:02.506 --> 41:05.008
"I apologize for being insolent"

41:05.009 --> 41:06.494
Go ahead

41:07.762 --> 41:09.888
"I apologize, sir"

41:09.889 --> 41:12.974
- "No, I apologize
for being insolent"

41:12.975 --> 41:15.602
Be sincere. I want a real apology

41:15.603 --> 41:17.855
Can you hurry up, please?

41:17.856 --> 41:20.316
- My moms waiting
- For your apology

41:20.317 --> 41:21.776
Let’s deal with this

41:21.777 --> 41:23.861
I want a sincere apology

41:23.862 --> 41:27.157
...that’ll stand for the rest of the year

41:27.158 --> 41:29.200
We won’t go on like this

41:29.201 --> 41:33.481
I apologize for being insolent.

41:34.123 --> 41:35.467
More conviction!

41:36.543 --> 41:38.961
I’m not saying it 50 times

41:38.962 --> 41:41.380
- You two,
What are you up to?

41:41.381 --> 41:43.758
We’re waiting

41:43.759 --> 41:45.969
Hurry, I’m listening

41:45.970 --> 41:48.638
I apologize for being insolent.

41:48.639 --> 41:50.125
May I go now, please?

41:58.525 --> 42:00.069
I didn’t mean it

42:11.456 --> 42:15.751
Two weeks ago, at the last meeting

42:15.752 --> 42:17.973
the teachers suggested

42:18.588 --> 42:22.592
introducing a penalty point system
for the students

42:22.593 --> 42:26.095
...based on the driving license system

42:26.096 --> 42:29.140
If student broke a rule

42:29.141 --> 42:31.601
...they would lose points

42:31.602 --> 42:34.980
As its teachers idea,
I’ll let them to speak

42:34.981 --> 42:39.527
Since last September...

42:39.528 --> 42:42.613
...we’ve noticed an increase
in problems within the school.

42:42.614 --> 42:45.867
Punishment has no effect
on the students

42:45.868 --> 42:47.494
So we had the idea

42:47.495 --> 42:49.037
...of a penalty system

42:49.038 --> 42:53.834
The students would have
for example six points each

42:53.835 --> 42:58.380
and depending on the misdeed
they’d lose one or two points.

42:58.381 --> 43:00.841
And when they run out of points?

43:00.842 --> 43:04.262
They go before the disciplinary committee.

43:04.263 --> 43:06.848
As a parents representative...

43:06.849 --> 43:11.853
...this is typical
of the schools bad habits...

43:11.854 --> 43:14.693
You always condemn the students...

43:15.275 --> 43:17.067
...but never praise them

43:17.068 --> 43:19.445
They earn praise on their own

43:19.446 --> 43:23.533
They do it with their grades,
by moving up a class

43:23.534 --> 43:26.202
and we do it in staff meetings...

43:26.203 --> 43:28.955
...by encouraging them to work.

43:28.956 --> 43:33.293
There’s the honor roll,
the congratulations.

43:33.294 --> 43:34.962
that all counts.

43:34.963 --> 43:36.880
In your system

43:36.881 --> 43:39.633
...you take away points for misdeeds

43:39.634 --> 43:41.344
but why not further

43:41.345 --> 43:44.847
...and give points to those
who do good things?

43:44.848 --> 43:46.891
Like gold stars.

43:46.892 --> 43:49.686
I’m all for praising the students.

43:49.687 --> 43:54.149
but if student collect points
and end up with 34 points, say,

43:54.150 --> 43:58.153
...That leaves room
for all kinds of trouble,

43:58.154 --> 43:59.572
...we can’t control

43:59.573 --> 44:02.491
Without going as far...

44:02.492 --> 44:03.785
as these imaginary 34 points

44:03.786 --> 44:07.247
...six points to start with,

44:07.248 --> 44:10.667
means they can cause trouble
without punishment.

44:10.668 --> 44:15.214
Losing a point or two
isn’t a real punishment.

44:15.215 --> 44:18.759
It can create
a dangerous sense of impunity.

44:18.760 --> 44:22.430
For me, the ideas
totally wrong-headed.

44:22.431 --> 44:23.873
In that case,

44:23.891 --> 44:25.850
...we could find a punishment

44:25.851 --> 44:30.294
...where the students
lose all their points in one go...

44:31.482 --> 44:35.866
But why bother with the points
in that case?

44:35.904 --> 44:38.113
It’s tricky

44:38.114 --> 44:40.408
- What you call a sense of impunity
gives us a room to maneuver,

44:40.409 --> 44:43.744
...When you’re dealing
with punishments.

44:43.745 --> 44:48.750
that are cut and dried,

44:48.751 --> 44:51.711
you can’t adapt them to each case

44:51.712 --> 44:53.839
I don’t agree

44:53.840 --> 44:55.424
The rules apply in the same way

44:55.425 --> 44:57.801
...to all the students

44:57.802 --> 44:59.929
They break them, they’re punished

44:59.930 --> 45:02.890
If not, why bother with rules?

45:02.891 --> 45:05.727
Dealing with extremely strict rules

45:05.728 --> 45:07.562
...creates the greatest tension...

45:07.563 --> 45:09.230
Take cell phones

45:09.231 --> 45:13.443
We agreed on a rule...

45:13.444 --> 45:14.820
...that cell phones
were not allowed in class

45:14.821 --> 45:17.323
Sorry, but I break that rule

45:17.324 --> 45:19.992
...because it wasn’t problem for me

45:19.993 --> 45:23.287
There’s room to be tolerant.

45:23.288 --> 45:25.612
The reign of the arbitrary.

45:25.749 --> 45:28.585
No, the law
and the spirit of the law.

45:28.586 --> 45:31.797
We could talk all night
but its not possible

45:31.798 --> 45:34.967
We have other topics to tackle.

45:34.968 --> 45:40.014
In particular, one vital issue,

45:40.015 --> 45:44.769
a very sensitive one,
concerning the staff coffee machine.

45:44.770 --> 45:48.022
It’s a sensitive issue, all right

45:48.023 --> 45:53.038
There’s a real problem this year...

45:54.322 --> 45:58.158
...The price of a coffee has gone up
from 40 centimes

45:58.159 --> 46:00.119
to 50 centimes

46:00.120 --> 46:02.413
That may seem petty...

46:02.414 --> 46:04.040
...but with several coffees a day,

46:04.041 --> 46:07.585
...at 8, 10 or 4
in the afternoon...

46:07.586 --> 46:12.132
it works out a lot

46:12.133 --> 46:15.324
...So we've clubbed together
to buy a coffee maker.

46:16.346 --> 46:20.474
- That way we can drink
as much coffee as we want...

46:20.475 --> 46:24.645
...without having to count.

46:24.646 --> 46:28.149
- Mr. Pierre will be delighted
to reply.

46:28.150 --> 46:34.150
- First of all, this machine
was installed in 2001...

46:35.183 --> 46:35.555
to replace a machine

46:35.742 --> 46:37.993
...that needed the intervention of...

46:37.994 --> 46:40.913
...an outside company for restocking

46:40.914 --> 46:44.625
...repairs etc.
It was very expensive

46:44.626 --> 46:46.435
And not at all profitable

46:46.754 --> 46:51.007
We switched to the new machine,
which isn’t profitable yet

46:51.008 --> 46:53.051
I’m sorry to hear that!

46:53.052 --> 46:55.214
And so we increased

46:55.472 --> 46:59.475
...the price of coffee by ten centimes.

46:59.476 --> 47:03.197
The thing has to be
economically viable

47:03.313 --> 47:08.211
- Nobody’s shocked?
- It’s clear and logical for me.

47:35.515 --> 47:38.392
- Good evening. Don’t move
- We have to go

47:38.393 --> 47:40.143
We haven’t finished

47:54.869 --> 47:57.621
" Respect

47:57.622 --> 48:01.208
" Adolescents
learn to respect their teachers...

48:01.209 --> 48:03.836
"..." because of threats...

48:03.837 --> 48:06.089
"..." or the fear of having problems

48:06.090 --> 48:08.591
" For starters, I respect you...

48:08.592 --> 48:11.678
"..." and respect must be mutual

48:11.679 --> 48:14.932
For instance,
I didn’t say you’re hysterical

48:14.933 --> 48:17.771
"..." so why do you say I am?

48:18.812 --> 48:21.272
" I’ve always respected you

48:21.273 --> 48:25.245
"..." so I don’t understand
why I have to write this.

48:26.111 --> 48:32.111
" I know you have it in for me
but don’t know why.

48:32.410 --> 48:34.953
" I shall sit at the back...

48:34.954 --> 48:38.720
"..." to avoid any other conflicts.

48:38.792 --> 48:41.263
" unless you come looking for them.

48:41.795 --> 48:43.838
" I admit I can be insolent...

48:43.839 --> 48:46.883
"..." but only if provoked.

48:46.884 --> 48:49.427
" I wont look at you again,.

48:49.428 --> 48:52.931
" so you cant say
my look is insolent.

48:52.932 --> 48:55.142
" In theory, in French class,

48:55.143 --> 48:58.562
"..." you talk about French,
not your grandma or sister

48:58.563 --> 49:01.034
"..." or girls periods.

49:01.525 --> 49:02.967
" And so, from now on,

49:02.985 --> 49:05.403
... " I wont spell to you again.."

49:05.404 --> 49:07.831
Signed Khoumba.

49:08.074 --> 49:09.866
- What is it?
- Secret.

49:09.867 --> 49:11.993
- A secret?
- A secret.

49:11.994 --> 49:14.878
It won’t stay a secret for long.

49:19.878 --> 49:22.505
Esmeralda,
Why have you changed places?

49:22.506 --> 49:23.849
No reason.

49:24.341 --> 49:25.989
I felt like it.

49:26.343 --> 49:29.859
- A problem?
- No, not at all.

49:30.264 --> 49:31.932
No problem.

49:31.933 --> 49:34.669
I wanted a change of scene.

49:41.568 --> 49:44.406
Ok, that’s enough.
Let’s get to work.

49:44.822 --> 49:46.527
No, sir, please!

49:47.283 --> 49:49.492
Please, sir!

49:49.493 --> 49:51.995
You’re just copying
what you did at home

49:51.996 --> 49:55.306
You’ve had plenty of time

49:56.459 --> 49:57.803
Esmeralda.

49:57.836 --> 50:01.146
I have to?

50:01.173 --> 50:03.540
Yes, absolutely.

50:06.220 --> 50:08.132
My name is Esmeralda Ouertani.

50:08.389 --> 50:09.556
I'm 14...

50:09.557 --> 50:12.350
...I live on Allee du Pere Dhuit...

50:12.351 --> 50:14.561
...Paris 20,

50:14.562 --> 50:17.856
...with my two parents and
my three brothers and sisters.

50:17.857 --> 50:18.941
Later,

50:18.942 --> 50:20.860
...I’d like to be a policewoman...

50:20.861 --> 50:24.739
...because people say
all policeman are bad,

50:24.740 --> 50:26.908
...and so we need good ones.

50:26.909 --> 50:29.828
If not, I’d like to be a rapper...

50:29.829 --> 50:33.594
...and I’m fan of Bakar, Medine,

50:33.666 --> 50:36.418
...Younes, Marvin and Mafiak1 Fry.

50:36.419 --> 50:37.544
Otherwise,

50:37.545 --> 50:41.882
I like eating, sleeping
and hanging out in the hood.

50:41.883 --> 50:43.227
Or rather?

50:43.427 --> 50:45.428
- The neighborhood.
- You can say it right.

50:45.429 --> 50:47.591
When you write,

50:47.640 --> 50:49.975
you use the standard style...

50:49.976 --> 50:53.645
Don’t make me correct you.

50:53.646 --> 50:55.234
Wey, go on.

50:57.817 --> 51:00.236
My names Wey, I’m Chinese.

51:00.237 --> 51:04.031
I’m 15, I have two sisters,
I’m the youngest.

51:04.032 --> 51:05.950
My hobby is playing video games

51:05.951 --> 51:08.584
at least 4 hours a day.

51:09.497 --> 51:12.207
I find it hard
using French correctly.

51:12.208 --> 51:15.043
It’s so hard expressing myself...

51:15.044 --> 51:18.005
...that others don’t understand me.

51:18.006 --> 51:21.153
That’s why I don’t communicate much.

51:21.969 --> 51:27.056
I hardly ever go out.
Nothing much interests me outside...

51:27.057 --> 51:31.603
The environment doesn’t suit me here
since I’m allergic

51:31.604 --> 51:33.722
...but i don’t know what.

51:33.856 --> 51:36.984
Allergic to yourself, that’s what.

51:36.985 --> 51:38.527
That’s good, Wey.

51:38.528 --> 51:41.405
I feel I know you better...

51:41.406 --> 51:44.552
...after hearing your self portrait.

51:44.702 --> 51:49.080
That’s the goal. To tell us things.

51:49.081 --> 51:51.625
He’s just happens to be good,
not ours

51:51.626 --> 51:53.669
No, not at all.

51:53.670 --> 51:55.712
I can congratulate Wey

51:55.713 --> 51:57.381
and I'd gladly congratulate you,

51:57.382 --> 52:01.052
if you manage to do it well.

52:01.053 --> 52:02.678
Rabah, read us...

52:02.679 --> 52:04.138
...your self portrait
- No.

52:04.139 --> 52:06.808
How can I congratulate you
if you don’t?

52:06.809 --> 52:08.152
I don’t need that.

52:08.185 --> 52:10.770
Make your mind up

52:10.771 --> 52:12.359
We’re listening.

52:12.940 --> 52:14.942
My name's Rabah. I’m 14.

52:14.943 --> 52:16.590
I listen to rap.

52:16.987 --> 52:20.823
I love my village in Kabylia
and go there every year.

52:20.824 --> 52:24.452
I like music, rap and slam.

52:24.453 --> 52:27.455
I have two brothers
but I don’t like school.

52:27.456 --> 52:29.416
I don’t like tramps.

52:29.417 --> 52:31.168
I like Zidane.

52:31.169 --> 52:34.254
I like to talk and I like
Psy 4 de la Rime's videos,

52:34.255 --> 52:35.741
...Go Marseille!

52:35.757 --> 52:38.217
We can manage without Marseille.

52:38.218 --> 52:39.343
Go Paris!

52:39.344 --> 52:42.263
We don’t need it in a self-portrait

52:42.264 --> 52:44.245
- That’s all.
- He skipped two lines.

52:44.308 --> 52:45.651
Cut it out.

52:48.104 --> 52:49.938
Go, dude.

52:49.939 --> 52:52.572
Boubacar!
- I like to make love

52:53.234 --> 52:56.323
I like to look good for the women

52:57.155 --> 52:58.739
and I like summer,

52:58.740 --> 53:00.653
...to see girls cleavage.

53:02.619 --> 53:04.996
Why not, Rabah?

53:04.997 --> 53:06.831
I never wrote that.

53:06.832 --> 53:08.875
It looks like your writing.

53:08.876 --> 53:10.220
No way!

53:12.547 --> 53:14.882
There’s no shame in liking cleavage.

53:14.883 --> 53:19.163
It's not a sin.

53:19.262 --> 53:23.057
Souleymane stop rocking
and read your self-portrait.

53:23.058 --> 53:25.476
- I’m very curious
- Huh?

53:25.477 --> 53:27.286
No, not huh.

53:27.730 --> 53:28.938
I wrote nothing.

53:28.939 --> 53:31.858
- I saw your writing earlier
- No, I wrote nothing

53:31.859 --> 53:33.110
You did

53:33.111 --> 53:35.538
- Nothing
- We're listening.

53:37.657 --> 53:40.284
I'm Souleymane.
I have nothing to say about me

53:40.285 --> 53:42.814
because no one knows me but me

53:44.873 --> 53:47.417
- Bravo!
- All right

53:47.418 --> 53:49.845
That’s good. A bit long maybe

53:53.841 --> 53:57.357
You can’t make the effort
that the others did?

53:57.929 --> 53:59.930
I don’t talk about myself.

53:59.931 --> 54:02.475
How come the others do?

54:02.476 --> 54:06.688
That’s their problem
I don’t talk about my life

54:06.689 --> 54:09.774
He just can’t write, that's all!

54:09.775 --> 54:11.371
What's up, you cop?

54:11.372 --> 54:13.153
You talking to me, cop?

54:13.154 --> 54:15.697
I can live with it

54:15.698 --> 54:18.033
- Enough!
- Arrest guys...

54:18.034 --> 54:20.578
...instead of talking to me.
Got your cuffs?

54:20.579 --> 54:22.741
Your breath stinks!

54:23.749 --> 54:26.000
- Chill.
- Heard of Aquafresh?

54:26.001 --> 54:27.443
Souleymane...

54:27.461 --> 54:29.546
there's no need
to be offensive.

54:29.547 --> 54:31.465
Need a toothbrush?

54:31.466 --> 54:32.674
Souleymane,

54:32.675 --> 54:38.055
...You’re a lot better
at oral insults than writing

54:38.056 --> 54:40.683
He can’t even write his name.

54:40.684 --> 54:43.227
Zip it! What does this say?

54:43.228 --> 54:44.937
Spare us your Koran.

54:44.938 --> 54:49.025
Shut it. What’s wrong
with the Koran.

54:49.026 --> 54:50.261
I’ll spare you when you calm dawn

54:50.278 --> 54:50.998
It’s the Koran.

54:51.154 --> 54:52.079
Bullshit!

54:52.196 --> 54:55.949
What’s that tattoo, Souleymane?

54:55.950 --> 54:57.576
Why are you showing it?

54:57.577 --> 55:00.254
He claims it's Koran

55:01.289 --> 55:03.958
What is it? Why are you showing us?

55:03.959 --> 55:07.378
It means shut your mouth.

55:07.379 --> 55:09.255
It doesn’t mean that

55:09.256 --> 55:12.634
So give us the real translation
Go on, tell us

55:12.635 --> 55:14.219
I don’t want to

55:14.220 --> 55:18.295
You show it in my class so tell us.

55:19.601 --> 55:22.186
It says here, right here:

55:22.187 --> 55:26.608
"If your words are less important
than silence, keep quiet."

55:26.609 --> 55:29.285
What I said

55:32.240 --> 55:34.199
It’s not what you said.

55:34.200 --> 55:36.201
Why isn’t it the same?

55:36.202 --> 55:38.537
It’s different.
I think it sounds better

55:38.538 --> 55:41.171
Yes it’s better put.

55:42.292 --> 55:45.753
If only you could write such
interesting things on paper,

55:45.754 --> 55:47.338
that would be great

55:47.339 --> 55:48.840
I think so too.

55:48.841 --> 55:51.063
That proves you can do it.

55:53.137 --> 55:55.764
After these fires few
self-portraits, Id like you,

55:55.765 --> 55:58.601
to rewrite them and polish them...

55:58.602 --> 56:02.813
...making sure you answer
the questions that we listed:

56:02.814 --> 56:05.342
what I like and don’t like...

56:05.484 --> 56:08.529
my qualities and flaws
who I’d like to be?

56:09.322 --> 56:10.909
Come in.

56:13.576 --> 56:16.620
Stand up please. Good morning.

56:16.621 --> 56:18.956
That goes for those at the back too

56:18.957 --> 56:22.884
Come on, stand up.

56:23.295 --> 56:26.464
Cherif, you heard me?
Everyone has to stand.

56:26.465 --> 56:30.385
It’s a way of greeting an adult

56:30.386 --> 56:33.263
It doesn’t mean
submission or humiliation.

56:33.264 --> 56:35.177
Good. Sit back down

56:36.768 --> 56:40.563
I’ve come to introduce
a new student.

56:40.564 --> 56:41.731
Carl.

56:41.732 --> 56:44.984
Try to make him welcome...

56:44.985 --> 56:47.821
...until the end of the year.

56:47.822 --> 56:51.485
Thank you

56:52.118 --> 56:55.162
Carl, go sit in the third row,
in that free place

56:55.163 --> 56:59.193
Khoumba, move your things

57:02.254 --> 57:04.881
Take a sheet of paper and a pen

57:04.882 --> 57:07.759
and try to catch up with the others

57:07.760 --> 57:09.246
...We’ll talk after

57:12.598 --> 57:16.852
Don’t forget the homework
for Monday without fail.

57:16.853 --> 57:19.530
Let’s finish with this

57:20.482 --> 57:24.300
Carl, stay here a minute or two

57:32.870 --> 57:34.214
Welcome

57:34.372 --> 57:36.999
I don’t know if you know

57:37.000 --> 57:40.920
but I'm Mr. Marin,
your class supervisor.

57:40.921 --> 57:44.275
If there’s a problem, tell me.

57:45.259 --> 57:48.720
I know who you are...
why you’re here

57:48.721 --> 57:50.138
The principal told me

57:50.139 --> 57:52.724
but that doesn’t matter for me

57:52.725 --> 57:55.686
We'll start from scratch here

57:55.687 --> 57:58.672
It will all go well.

57:58.899 --> 58:01.859
You’ve seen that we...

58:01.860 --> 58:04.570
Were on self-portraits to be
handed in next Monday.

58:04.571 --> 58:07.866
- Maybe you could do one too
- OK.

58:07.867 --> 58:09.881
Know when the next class is?

58:12.330 --> 58:14.164
Monday, 9.30

58:14.165 --> 58:15.974
Good.

58:17.544 --> 58:20.118
You like French?

58:21.131 --> 58:23.190
Like everyone, I guess.

58:26.554 --> 58:28.888
That doesn’t mean much.

58:28.889 --> 58:30.846
